\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, the effectiveness of decision-making during radio-network planning
 is tightly coupled with the precision achieved by the propagation model
 used.
 In order to obtain a radio-propagation model that most accurately reflects
 the propagation characteristics of the area covered by each radio cell
 in the network, the parameters of the mathematical model are tuned using
 field-measurement campaigns.
 Parameter tuning using this method depends on existing field-measurement
 data, which are taken before hand over the area covered by the target network
 cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Parameter tuning of the radio-prediction model
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\backslash
label{sec:Parameter-tuning
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective here is thus improve the quality performance of a given mathematic
al model, used for radio-propagation calculations, by fine-tuning its configurab
le parameters as per-cell basis.
 In order to do this, we apply a state-of-the-art analytical approach, based
 on least squares method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yang_A_linear_least_square_method_of_propagation_model_tuning_for_3G_radion_network_planning:2008"

\end_inset

, thus combining field measurements to fit the parameters of the mathematical
 model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to automatically adapt the parameters of the mathematical model
 for each of the cells targeted by the optimization.
 That is, starting from an a-priori best-known set of parameters, empirically
 calculated by the radio engineers at Telekom Slovenije, d.d., this approach
 adapts the model parameters so that the deviation of the radio-propagation
 prediction to a given set of field measurements is minimized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of our work, this translates to fine tuning the parameters
 of the LOS part of the path-loss prediction model, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $pl_{\mathrm{LOS}}(d_{(x,y)},\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 The adjustable parameters are the elements of vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=(a_{0},a_{1},a_{2},a_{3})$
\end_inset

, namely
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 the reference loss or offset;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 the loss slope due to distance of the receiver from the transmitter;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 the loss slope due to height of the transmitter antenna;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 the loss slope due to the combined effect of the distance and height of
 the antenna.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter tuning is performed per cell to improve local fitting of the
 radio predictions.
 The steps to be completed are: collect and process field-measurement data,
 and solve the particular system of linear equations.
 The resulting solution is the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 of the target cell, with its values locally adapted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following, we denote the default parameters of the radio-propagation
 model with these values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 38.0,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 32.0,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 -12.0, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 0.1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Field measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In mobile networks, a moving mobile constantly performs cell selection/reselecti
on and handover in order to keep the best possible connection to the network.
 Within this context, the best connection is selected by measuring the signal
 strength or quality of the neighboring cells.
 In LTE networks, a mobile measures two parameters on reference signal,
 namely the Reference Signal Received Power (RSRP) and the Reference Signal
 Received Quality (RSRQ).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a certain frequency bandwidth, RSRP measures the average received power
 over the resource elements that carry cell-specific reference signals.
 RSRP is applicable in idle (e.g.
 waiting for a call) and connected (e.g.
 during a call) modes.
 During the procedure of cell selection/reselection in idle mode, RSRP is
 used.
 On the other hand, RSRQ is only applicable when the mobile is in connected
 mode.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The radio-coverage calculation involves predicting the network coverage
 over a certain region, and thus to the users' mobiles within it.
 Hence, in the first place, we are interested on accurately predicting the
 best connection the mobile would select in idle mode and the RSRP field
 measurements it uses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our case, the field measurements, representing the RSRP at a given location,
 are collected using a small truck equipped with the spectrum analyzer Rohde
 & Schwarz.
 The spectrum analyzer is connected to an external omni antenna mounted
 on the roof of the truck, at roughly 2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

meters above the ground, taking measurements at a rate of 50
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hz???, with the symbol rate set to ???
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Mhz.
 To accurately establish the measurement location points, a GPS unit was
 used.
 The measurement locations covered most of the streets within the target
 area, with over 300,000 individual field-measurement points taken at more
 of more than 150 network cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To minimize the error impact in measured RSRP and estimated location, all
 field measurements are processed so that a single value, the median
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The median is the numerical value separating the higher half of a sample
 set from the lower half.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, is calculated for each of the measured locations.
 The resulting RSRP is then used to estimate the path-loss prediction at
 the location corresponding to each of the measurements, which resolution
 matches those of the digital elevation model and clutter data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Linear least squares
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note the linear relationship between the predicted loss
 
\begin_inset Formula $pl(d_{(x,y)},\beta)$
\end_inset

 and the components of vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, for this is a necessary condition for the least-squares method to find
 a solution.
 Following this method, the parameter fitting of the propagation model is
 based on the minimization of an observed error, i.e.
 the sum of the squared difference between the predicted and measured RSRP,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
E(c)=\sum_{i=1}^{m_{c}}(p_{c}-pl_{c}(d_{(x,y)},\beta_{c})-fm_{i})^{2},\label{eq:least_squares_error}
\end{multline}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $E(c)$
\end_inset

 is the observed error for cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the transmit power of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $fm_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th field measurement out of a set of measurements of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 with cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Simulations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulations carried out for this part of our work comprise building
 the matrices of observed-error values, 
\begin_inset Formula $E(c)$
\end_inset

, for each cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in the target network.
 The linear systems of equations are then individually solved by applying
 the linear least squares method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yang_A_linear_least_square_method_of_propagation_model_tuning_for_3G_radion_network_planning:2008"

\end_inset

, which involves the evaluation of one radio-coverage prediction per cell.
 Each system holds a unique solution for each cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, denoted by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Percentage of clutter-category proportions for each of the test networks
 used.
 The category legend is given in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Clutter-categories"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Proportion_of_clutter_for_test_networks"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

