\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results calculated by the optimization process are shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Clutter-optimization-solutions"

\end_inset

.
 The solutions are given for each of the test networks, along with typical
 default loss values due to clutter.
 Hyphens represent clutter categories for which there are no field measurements
 available.
 Consequently, it is not possible to calculate an objective-function value
 for them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimized loss for the first clutter category, 0, representing urban
 area without buildings, is larger than the default value in all three networks.
 This may be attributed to the fact that ...??? As for the category 1, representing
 suburban area, the value for Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{1}$
\end_inset

 is lower than the default one, mainly because this network is deployed
 over a predominant agricultural area, i.e.
 suburban areas are less dense here.
 On the other hand, the value for Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 is larger, indicating a building density above the average, whereas for
 Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{3}$
\end_inset

, the value could not be calculated due to lack of measurements.
 A similar behavior may be observed for category 2, representing urban area.
 However, for category 3, representing dense urban area, the optimized losses
 of all three networks are lower than the default value, indicating dense
 urban areas here are not as dense as the average case.
 Representing agricultural area, category 4 gets a value very close to the
 default one for Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{1}$
\end_inset

 and Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{3}$
\end_inset

, whereas for Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 the value is lower, indicating the most of this kind of land is not being
 exploited near the city.
 As for category 5, representing forests, the results are well corresponded
 with the kind of forest dominating each of the test networks, being those
 of Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{1}$
\end_inset

 and Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{3}$
\end_inset

 more dense due to leave foliage, whereas as for Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 the forests are mostly coniferous and more sparse.
 Keeping the default loss values for categories 6, 7 and 8, we move on to
 category 9, representing water, for which the results of all three networks
 indicate creeks and rivers in these areas are mostly surrounded by forests
 (Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{1}$
\end_inset

) or buildings (Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

), since none of the regions lays by the sea.
 As for the industrial areas, denoted by clutter category 10, show lower
 loss values than the typical default, indicating very sparse industrial
 buildings (Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{1}$
\end_inset

) and a higher density of mostly commercial buildings for Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and Net
\begin_inset Formula $_{3}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results clearly show the benefit of the optimization of losses due
 to land usage or clutter, by finely adapting these values to local conditions
 within the environment where these networks are deployed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statistical analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the stochastic nature of the optimization algorithm, we have
 collected the results from 30 independent runs, in order to have enough
 data for the results to be statistically relevant.
 In other words, the robustness of the solutions presented in the previous
 section is analyzed here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To this end, Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Solutions-analysis"

\end_inset

 shows the solutions reached by the DASA for each of three test networks.
 The calculated signal losses are thus depicted with the minimum, maximum
 and average values for every clutter category, along with their standard
 deviation.
 Similarly as before, hyphens represent clutter categories for which there
 are no field measurements available, and thus they cannot be optimized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Statistical analysis of the optimization solutions for each test network.
 All values are expressed in dB.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Solutions-analysis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
